{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774293491,"nonce":"/I4sbkH5KB+CmPaecGYaCEY8/Xc=","title":"Part 2.5 experiment: compare PAI-ASF under standard backprop, CVaR, and APT","message":"## Summary\n\nExtend Part 2 with a focused experiment comparing training objectives while holding the training method (PAI-ASF) fixed. The question: does worst-case-oriented training produce the missing behavioral signatures (especially peak velocity increase)?\n\n## Training Protocol\n\nAll models use PAI-ASF (SISU = beta ~ U[0,1] scaling perturbations). The variable is the training objective:\n\n1. **Standard backprop** (existing Part 2 baseline): minimize E[L] over perturbation distribution\n2. **CVaR 10%**: for each SISU level, sample K realizations, backprop only through worst 10% of losses\n3. **APT (3-5 inner steps)**: adversarial perturbation training — inner loop finds worst-case w via gradient ascent, outer loop trains against it\n\nPerturbation type: gusts (default) and/or constant fields. Use default hyperparameters. 5 replicates per condition = 3 training conditions x 5 replicates = 15 models minimum.\n\n## Evaluation Protocol\n\nUse part2.plant_perts-style analysis:\n- SISU levels [0.0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0]\n- Perturbation amplitudes [0.0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0] (in units of training std)\n- Center-out reaches, 16 directions\n\n## Primary Questions\n\n1. Does CVaR or APT produce increased peak velocities at high SISU?\n2. Do feedback gain curves (from feedback perturbation analysis) differ?\n3. Does the extrapolation behavior (SISU \u003e 1) become more consistent?\n4. Does APT produce qualitatively different trajectory shapes (e.g., more vigorous initial movement)?\n5. How does training cost (wall time, convergence) compare?\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- CVaR implementation: straightforward, ~10 lines of JAX in the training loop\n- APT implementation: inner gradient ascent loop, more involved but still pure JAX\n- Feedbax Studio integration for training method selection: separate issue in Feedbax repo (CVaR easy, APT harder due to model-specific inner loop)\n- May want to also include the movement-time penalty (accumulating cost) as a fourth condition, since this was identified as the most impactful single change for peak velocity. Could be orthogonal to CVaR/APT.\n\n## Expected Results\n\n- Standard backprop: reproduces existing Part 2 results (no peak velocity increase, graded gain modulation)\n- CVaR: modest shift toward worst-case behavior, possibly some velocity increase, stronger tail performance\n- APT: strongest candidate for H-infinity-like signatures — peak velocity increase, non-specific stiffening, consistent extrapolation\n\n## Notes\n\nThis experiment is preliminary/exploratory — results inform whether to invest in a full Part 3 with these methods. If APT shows the behavioral signatures and standard backprop doesn't, that's a strong argument for the paper's narrative about the gap between expected-cost and worst-case optimization in biological motor control.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}